// @test: typecheck-pass
// @level: L0
// @tier: 0
// @tags: modules, header-validation, forward-decl, vuva-mod-med-1
// @description: VVA #145 / MOD-MED-1 — module header validation.
//
// `module foo;` (forward-decl form) at the top of a file is supposed
// to be loaded from `<dir>/foo.vr` or `<dir>/foo/mod.vr`. When neither
// candidate exists, the compiler used to silently accept the
// declaration; users frequently expected Rust-style "this file IS
// module foo" semantics and got dangling decls instead.
//
// This file declares a forward-decl `module nonexistent_helper;`
// but does NOT create the corresponding source file. The compiler
// must emit a `E_MODULE_HEADER_FORWARD_DECL_NO_SOURCE` warning
// pointing at this line. The build still succeeds — it's a soft
// failure that signals "your dotted path won't resolve at use sites".
//
// We use typecheck-pass (not typecheck-fail) because the header
// validation is non-blocking; the warning is the diagnostic, not the
// failure. A separate runner test could verify the warning code is
// emitted; this VCS file pins the "no-error" half.

module nonexistent_helper;

fn main() {
    print("dangling-forward-decl");
}
